content.problemStatement:
In C++, Complex Boolean Expressions are expressions that involve multiple conditions combined using logical operators such as:

- `&&` (Logical AND) – true only if all conditions are true
- `||` (Logical OR) – true if at least one condition is true
- `!` (Logical NOT) – reverses the truth value of a condition

These expressions are useful for making decisions based on multiple comparisons or rules. They’re widely used in `if`, `if-else`, `while`, and `for` statements. (This will be discussed later.)

**Syntax**
```cpp
if ((condition1 && condition2) || condition3) {
    // code to execute if the condition is true
}
```
---

**Example**
```cpp
#include 
using namespace std;

int main() {
    bool hasID = true;              // Student has an ID card
    float temperature = 98.4;       // Body temperature in Fahrenheit
    bool isLate = false;            // Student arrived on time

    // Check with AND (&&) operator
    if (hasID && temperature <= 99.0) {
        cout << "Access granted to the exam hall." << endl;
    } else {
        cout << "Access denied!" << endl;
    }

    // Check with OR (||) operator
    if (hasID || temperature <= 99.0) {
        cout << "At least one condition met: Entry may be considered with caution." << endl;
    } else {
        cout << "No entry at all!" << endl;
    }

    // Check with NOT (!) operator
    if (!isLate) {  // If student is NOT late
        cout << "You are on time for the exam." << endl;
    } else {
        cout << "You are late!" << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

**Expected Output**
```default
Access granted to the exam hall.
At least one condition met: Entry may be considered with caution.
You are on time for the exam.
```

